On April 6, 2024, one (1) 5-gallon pail of sodium hydroxide was crushed in transit and released approximately five (5) gallons of product to the trailer interior and adjacent freight. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental (HCE) to remediate the impacted site. HCE personnel overpacked the damaged pail in one (1) 55-gallon drum, then deployed neutralizer to the release. The crew further remediated the site using absorbent pads. All sodium hydroxide-impacted materials were containerized in one (1) additional 55-gallon drum for disposal.

While completing a routine 10-Day facility inspection, a Veolia employee noticed a wet spot under a pallet of drums. Upon further inspection the employee noticed a pinhole on the side of the drum approximately 10 inches from the top. Approximately 1 gallon of material leaked from the drum through the pinhole throughout the weekend. The drum was overpacked and the spill was cleaned using oil dry.
column170: Although it is unclear what caused the hole in the drum, it is important to ensure that the customer is using proper packaging and handling procedures for shipping containers before offering the waste to Veolia. Also, Veolia employees must do thorough inspections on all containers to ensure that container integrity is not compromised in any way at the time of pick up from the customer.

column169: XPO Logistics terminal LFW experienced a UN3098 NIL 8 release from a 2.5-gallon poly jerrican. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 0.5 cups of product released to a 1.5’ x 3” area of the trailer floor. The remaining material in the jug released into the poly bag/absorbents the pail was contained too prior to the crew’s arrival. The empty damaged jug, poly bag, absorbent and sodium bicarb were placed into a 55-gallon vented poly drum. The trailer floor was cleaned and neutralized with sodium bicarb. The impacted oil dri, neutralizer, impacted pallet wood, and poly 5-gallon pail which held the absorbents were placed into a second 55-gallon vented poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

On April 4, 2024, one (1) 275-gallon tote of corrosive liquid was punctured by a forklift and released approximately 115-gallons of product to the trailer interior and pavement beneath. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental (HCE) to remediate the impacted site. HCE personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted roadway/trailer interior and swept them in with hand tools. HCE utilized an additional tote to complete a gravity feed from the impacted 275-gallon tote. All spent absorbents, absorbent pads and collected waste were collected and containerized into six (6) 55-gallon metal drums and PPE was containerized into a separate 55-gallon open top poly drum. All were labeled and set aside for terminal disposal.

column169: SequenceEvent: The box was unloaded off the trailer. Then the box was transported to the van that was to deliver the box. An hour later, the driver of the van saw the box was leaking white small granules. The driver called a manager who came over to the van with gloves, broom, dustpan and a red hazmat plastic container. The manager put the box inside the red hazmat plastic container and swept up any granules that came out of the box. He then gently put the granules inside the box. The box was then transported to the hazmat cage by the Ops Admin. DescribePack: The bottom of the plastic bucket had a dent on the corner. The dent was about 3" long.  The bottom of the plastic bucket has a crack going along the outside seem about 8 inches long. Upon inspection saw underneath this plastic bottom was another plastic bottom. This inside plastic bottom was cracked in several places. The cracks ranged from 7 inches to 3 inches. I could see the product had leaked out of these cracks and the very outside crack. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The box was turned upside down and placed inside a red plastic hazmat container. The leakage of the product stopped since the cracks were on the bottom of the plastic bucket that was inside the box.

R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted site. The damaged 55-gallon drum of product was placed into one (1) 85-gallon drum. All containers were staged onsite for future disposal.

Hepaco was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted an 8ft-by-50ft area of the trailer floor and a 25ft-by-100ft area of the concrete lot and estimated that seventy-five (75) gallons of material was released from one (1) 275-gallon poly tote. Hepaco personnel deployed a granular absorbent and a neutralizer to the impacted areas. The spent material was gathered and containerized into eight (8) 55-gallon poly drums. The generated waste was transported to the local Dayton Freight terminal and placed in a secure location for the terminal to coordinate disposal. The generated waste will remain onsite for the Dayton Freight team to coordinate disposal.

XPO-XTM contacted ERTS regarding a punctured leaking tote containing Predator MR2516. The tote was  punctured by a forklift and released approximately 35-gallons of product onto the wooden trailer floor and  concrete underneath the trailer. The trailer floor impact area was 18'x18' and the impact area underneath the  trailer was 8'x20'. A Contractor performed a tote transfer, cut-up pallets that were impacted by the release, and  cleaned-up the release on the trailer floor. Five drums of waste were generated for disposal. No storm-drains,  waterways, or soil were affected by this incident.

column169: XPO Logistics terminal XAY experienced a UN2922 Nalcon 7634 release from 275-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 100-gallons of product released to 60' x 20' area of the concrete dock and a 40' x 15' area of the asphalt parking lot due to a forklift puncture. The material was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one. Absorbents were then deployed and worked into the impacted area to clean the release. All impacted absorbents were containerized into (8) 55-gallon poly drums. The damaged tote was then cut up and containerized along with impacted absorbents and PPE into a cubic yard box. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: SequenceEvent: Package came off of truck in Unload notably wet, was placed into lined tote immediately and moved to safe area. Unable to determine if this occurred when initially loaded to trailer or during transit to our station. Upon opening outer packaging found one of four 4L bottles of water (non-hazardous) had somehow broken during shipping causing water to release inside package and eventually seep out as well. DescribePack: There were corrugated moldings around each of the four bottles to help protect during shipping but evidently was not enough to keep one bottle from getting broken. When that happened water leaked out inside, compromising structural integrity of inner, outer packaging and causing the box/moldings to tear and distort due to weight of 3 non-broken bottles. Bottle was already broken coming off of trailer so no knowledge of what directly caused damage to occur. DurationRel: 2 and MitigateEffect: Water had already leaked out due to bottle being broken completely. Cleaned up all wet areas in trailer and unload to re-establish safe working environment. Thankfully as stated through this report, the box was labeled as a Hazmat but did not contain any hazardous contents. Not sure if it was a mix-up by shipper when assigning labels to packages or what cause was, but no hazardous contents were in package or leaked out.

On April 9, 2024, one (1) 350-gallon tote of acetone had a faulty valve and released approximately one (1) gallon of product to the trailer interior and dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Lone Star Hazmat (LSH) to remediate the impacted site. Crews transferred the remaining contents of the damaged stainless steel tote into six (6) 55-gallon steel drums and labeled not to ship. The impacted surfaces were remediated with absorbents and all waste collected and contained in one (1) 55-gallon drum. All waste and the empty tote were staged onsite at the terminal.

He should have walked the unload hose several times to the bleeder valve on the trailer and or pump to do a controlled drain off of approximately 3 gallons on the hoses on either side of the pump to create enough headspace to safely disconnect without having product right at the hose end.

Crews deployed additional granular absorbents to the impacted area and worked them in with hand tools. Cleaners and absorbent pads were utilized to remove any residual product. The package was brought in and examined and it was determined that there were four non-spillable batteries inside, two of which showed scorch marks from a small fire. The package was placed into a steel salvage drum and is being help pending disposition. The NRC was notified of the fire at approximately 2300, report # 1396190.

column169: XPO Logistics contacted ERTS regarding a roadside release of Kurifloc 7115 from a 275-gallon tote as a result of  improper loading / inadequate preparation for transportation. The tote became crushed under falling freight  breaking the cap and causing the release during transit. Approximately 10-gallons of product released onto the  trailer floor, the asphalt beneath the trailer, and the concrete parking lot. The impact areas include the trailer  floor: 4'x4', asphalt beneath the trailer: 2'x8', and concrete parking lot: 3'x20'. A Contractor secured the freight for the trailer to pull into a parking lot where a tote transfer was performed and the trailer floor was neutralized  with white vinegar. The transferred tote was loaded onto trailer while the damaged tote was taken by the  Contractor to XPO’s Shreveport, LA terminal to be cut-up and containerized for waste disposal. Additionally,  one drum containing PPE, impacted oil dry, and impacted absorbent rags was generated for waste disposal. No  storm-drains, soil, or waterways were impacted by this incident.

On April 3, 2024, one (1) 55-gallon drum of phosphoric acid was punctured by a forklift and released approximately fifteen (15) gallons of product to the dock floor and pallet. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from ES+ to remediate the impacted site. E3+ personnel deployed absorbents to the release and worked them in with hand tools. The pallet was disassembled and containerized in one (1) 55-gallon drum. The damaged drum of phosphoric acid was overpacked in one (1) 85-gallon drum. All spent absorbents and impacted materials were containerized in one (1) additional 55-gallon drum. The three (3) waste drums were staged onsite for disposal.

SequenceEvent: Package had been unloaded and was on van line ready to be loaded on van when the loading package handler saw that the box was wet. Package was set aside on a spill containment pallet, then placed in a lined container shortly after. DescribePack: 2 of the 4 jugs were packed in the box upside down, with the caps in contact with the bottom of the box. This allowed stress to be applied to caps, leading to them beginning to leak inside the plastic bags. The plastic bags then also began leaking, soiling the box and other contents. The caps had some tape wrapped around them, but this appears to have been ineffective at prevent leakage. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The external box contained mostly all of the spillage, becoming wet in the process. There was no visible wetness on conveyor belt, and only a slightly damp spot of the spill pallet. Spill neutralizer was applied to the spot. Package was placed in a lined container during inspection and reporting. During this, contents began to leak more due to manipulation. All leakage was contained by liner.

SequenceEvent: Package arrived in QA in a repacked Fedex box that was soaked and discolored. Package had no indication or labeling of hazmat status. Package had been previously DPR'd and poorly repacked at the destination station 62 and returned. It was loosely packed in the box and leaked a significant amount out by the time it arrived at 625. Seeing the package, I checked the SDS for hazmat status where it said it was regulated, UN3264. DescribePack: Cap was on and there is a plug underneath, but the plug appeared to not seal on one side of the hole and was leaking significantly out from under the cap. DurationRel: 2 and MitigateEffect: Package was immediately isolated upright in a lined Tote.

SequenceEvent: Package was brought to our attention after it was found wet and leaking. Package was promptly placed into a tote and transferred to the hazmat cage for further inspection. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Package was placed into a tote to mitigate any additional spillage.

On April 13, 2024, at 2240 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in Glade Spring, Virginia regarding the release of approximately 45 gallons of METHYL ETHYL KETONE (UN1193, 3, III) from (4) 55-gallon DM’s. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release was caused by multiple pallets breaking creating punctures and was contained to the trailer floor and a 1ft x 1ft area of asphalt beneath the trailer. Contractors were able to clean the release with absorbents and the proper PPE. All waste generated was placed in (1) 55-gallon DM, and the 4 damaged drums with remaining product were each placed in 85-gallon DM overpacks and was taken offsite by contractors.

column169: XPO Logistics terminal UPH experienced an over the road release of UN1866 Tremco Puma Primer from a 6-gallon metal pail. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct containment and cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-gallons of product released due to a broken pallet puncturing the pail. The majority of the release impacted a 6’ x 4’ area of the wooden trailer floor with approximately 1 cup impacting a 3” x 6” area of the gravel rocks below the trailer. The damaged pail was collected with oil dri into a 55-gallon metal drum. Absorbent pads were then used to clean the impacted trailer and crew utilized hand tools to scrap up the impacted rocks. The impacted rags, damaged pallet, impacted gravel rocks, PPE, and poly were placed into a separate 55-gallon metal drum. The waste was transported back to the XPO terminal in Phoenix, AZ for terminal personnel to manage.

SequenceEvent: The package was discovered at the re-pack area at this station. It was brought over to the QA dept for further inspection. The contents were researched and examined and found to be leaking. An SDS was obtained and found to be hazardous. The item and its packaging was then placed in a haardous tote and processed as a damaged hazmat. DescribePack: The bottom of the package was wet and open. Inside there were three plastic containers with plastic tape placed over the caps and all three were placed in a plastic bag within the package. The image on Spidr indicates the package was originally larger and totaling 49.00pounds and only had a label indicating it was fragile. One of the three containers conaining cyco platinum ph up had significant volumn missing due to a loose cap that was leaking when the container was flipped upside down. DurationRel: 4 and MitigateEffect: The package was placed in a hazmat tote once it was  discovered that it was hazardous. Proper PPE was donned, and the processing of a damaged hazmat was initiated.

column169: XPO Logistics terminal XCW experienced a release from (4) 275-gallon poly totes. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 20-gallons of UN2734 Tri-Act 1800 released from (2) 275-gallon poly totes due to forklift punctures. Approximately 20-gallons of UN2920 Tri-Act 1820 also released from (2) 275-gallon poly totes due to a bent metal cage and a forklift puncture. The products collectively impacted a 6’ x 1’ area of the trailer floor, 20’ x 8’ area of the concrete lot, and a 40’ x 15’ & 10’ x 3’ areas of the concrete dock floor. All 4 totes of material were transferred into new totes for shipment on. Absorbent & citric acid solution were then deployed and worked into the impacted areas to clean and neutralize the release. The damaged totes were then cut up and containerized along with all impacted absorbents into (8) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

XPO Logistics terminal NCH experienced a UN1824 Greasestrip Plus release from a box containing (4) 1-gallon poly jugs as well as a release of UN3264 Lime-A-Way from a box containing (4) 1-gallon poly jugs. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-gallons of each product, (4-gallons combined) released to a 4’ x 4’ area of the trailer floor due to a forklift puncture. Soda ash solution and oil dri were deployed to clean and neutralize the impacted area. All impacted absorbents, cardboard, PPE, and the two empty pails of UN3264 Lime-A-Way were placed into a 55-gallon poly drum. The two empty jugs, and two damaged jugs of UN1824 Greasestrip Plus were placed into a separate 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

On 03-21-2024 the CN Dangerous Goods Team was notified by a CN Transportation employee that an FRA Hazmat inspector observed liquid around the Plug of the Liquid valve in the protective housing on Tank Car # PPRX55097 while performing a regulatory compliance check at the CN Council Bluffs Yard in Council Bluffs, IA. A CN response contractor was dispatched to the yard to investigate. A CN emergency response contractor was dispatched to the location for mitigation. The CN contractor found liquid around the plug of the liquid valve. Plug was tool tight (not able to move by hand) but no teflon tape was observed. The CN emergency response contractor ensured that the valve handle was seated properly. Plug was removed and liquid was observed between the plug and valve seat. Liquid was cleared and the valve seat was observed for 5 mins to check for any continued leaks. Protective housing was then secured using an HMRI security seal.

column169: On April 10, 2024, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN1263 was cracked and released approximately less than one (<1) gallon of product to the loading dock floor and pallet. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental (HCE) to remediate the impacted site.  Crews utilized an 85-gallon open top drum to overpack and contain the damaged 55-gallon drum. HCE personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted loading dock floor and worked them in with hand tools. Crews utilized absorbent pads to collect any residual product from the impacted areas. All UN1263 impacted material was collected and containerized in one (1) 15-gallon drum. All waste was staged onsite for disposal by R+L.
